---
export const metadata = {
  title: "Member of the Family: My Story of Charles Manson, Life Inside His Cult, and the Darkness",
  author: "Dianne Lake",
  year: 1998,
  rating: "★★★☆☆",
  completed: true,
  summary:
    "An account of a member of Manson's famous family which participated in famous murders",
};

const title = metadata.title;
const author = metadata.author;
const year = metadata.year;
const rating = metadata.rating;
const yearDisplay = year ?? '—';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />

  <title>{title} Review</title>

  <style>
    :root {
      --bg: #f8f8f5;
      --text: #111;
      --muted: #666;
      --border: #d8d8d8;
      --max-width: 72ch;
    }

    html {
      scroll-behavior: smooth;
    }

    body {
      margin: 0;
      background: var(--bg);
      color: var(--text);

      font-family: Georgia, serif;
      font-size: 19px;
      line-height: 1.72;

      padding: 3rem 1.5rem 6rem;
    }

    .container {
      max-width: var(--max-width);
      margin: 0 auto;
      position: relative;
    }

    h1 {
      font-size: 3rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      letter-spacing: -0.03em;

      margin-bottom: 0.2rem;
    }

    h2, h3 {
      font-size: 1.35rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      margin: 2rem 0 1rem;
    }

    .meta {
      color: var(--muted);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      font-family: monospace;

      margin-bottom: 3rem;
    }

    p {
      margin-bottom: 1.7rem;
      text-align: justify;
    }

    .review-incomplete {
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--muted);
    }

    blockquote {
      margin: 2.5rem 0;
      padding-left: 1.2rem;

      border-left: 2px solid var(--border);

      color: #333;
      font-style: italic;
    }

    .section-break {
      text-align: center;
      color: var(--muted);
      margin: 3rem 0;
      letter-spacing: 0.15em;
    }

    .sidenote {
      float: right;
      clear: right;

      width: 15rem;

      margin-right: -18rem;
      margin-top: 0.3rem;

      padding-left: 0.9rem;
      border-left: 1px solid var(--border);

      color: var(--muted);

      font-size: 0.78rem;
      line-height: 1.5;
    }

    .sidenote code {
      font-size: 0.75rem;
      background: #efefea;
      padding: 0.05rem 0.2rem;
    }

    @media (max-width: 1200px) {
      .sidenote {
        display: none;
      }
    }

    a {
      color: inherit;
    }

    hr {
      border: none;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
      margin: 4rem 0;
    }
  </style>
</head>

<body>
  <main class="container">

    <h1>{title}</h1>

    <div class="meta">
      {author} · {yearDisplay} · {rating}
    </div>

    <p>
        Charles Manson is among the most famous murderers in United States History in the company of 
        Ted Bundy, Ted Kacysnki, and John Wayne Gacy. But unlike them, he did not actually commit the murders for which he is remembered: instead he inspired
        his cult-members to commit murders on his command. Manson had a unique ability to manipulate people 
        beliefs, tehcniques, and his methods of control. 
    </p>
    <p></p>

        Dianne Lake's account proceeds by describing her home life and her families absorption into the counter-culture movement of the 60s led by her father an unstable
        character. Her family slowly morphs from a suburban family into hippies who under the guise of providing more independence pay less and 
        less attention to her until she searches for support and love and a sense of belonging. Manson provided that sense of belonging she lacked and and used it to mantain control 
        over his commune of women. They were used to recruit (sometimes sexually), and preform all other tasks. <span class = "sidenote">Lake describes how a key ability of Manson was convincing his commune through "postulation" basically maniefesting things and the future into existence. However, 
            Lake realizes that this was Manson using his ability to manipulate (often financially) to predict an outcome he knew he could create
            </span> Manson main method was keen observation of the person including 
        minutiae of details then identifying and satisfying their desires. <span class = "sidenote"> Manson had read how to win friends and influence people which is a possible origin to this technique </span>
       He wasn't limited to persuasion however: Dianne describes instances of physical abuse 
        combined with nurturing aftercare that led to victims blamimng themselves rather than Manson. All of Manson's techniques were especially effective due to the number of 
        possible victims at the time : California was a hotbed of cult activity as children were given independence earlier than before. Lake describes how he would carefully screen 
        potential selecting for status <span class ="sidenote"> Lake describes Manson's encounter with Dennis Wilson of the Beach Boys where Manson wanted to use every tool to 
            potentially get access to Wilson's music connections to further his ambitions see: look at your game girl</span> and vulnerability. 

        


      
      
    <div class="section-break">⁂</div>
    </p>

  </main>
</body>
</html>
